<h3 id="production-config" permalink="production-config">Production Config</h3>
<p>In production, you should configure a session store that can be <a href="/documentation/concepts/deployment/scaling">shared across multiple servers</a>.  To do so, you will need to set <code>sails.config.session.adapter</code>, set up your session database, and then add any other configuration specific to the Connect session adapter you are using.</p>
<h5 id="configuring-redis-as-your-session-store" permalink="configuring-redis-as-your-session-store">Configuring Redis as Your Session Store</h5>
<p>The most popular session store for production Sails applications is Redis.  It works great as a session database since it is inherently good at ephemeral storage, but Redis&apos; popularity probably has more to do with the fact that, if you are using sockets and plan to scale your app to multiple servers, you will <a href="/documentation/concepts/deployment/scaling">need a Redis instance</a> anyway.</p>
<p>The easiest way to set up Redis as your app&apos;s shared session store is to uncomment the following line in <code>config/session.js</code>:</p>
<pre><code class="javascript">adapter: &apos;connect-redis&apos;,
</code></pre><!-- __LANG=%%__ -->
<p>Then install the <a href="https://github.com/tj/connect-redis" target="_blank">connect-redis</a> session adapter as a dependency of your app:</p>
<pre><code class="bash">npm install connect-redis@~3.0.2 --save --save-exact
</code></pre><!-- __LANG=%%__ -->
<p>The following settings are optional, since if no redis configuration other than <code>adapter</code> is provided, Sails assumes you want it to use a redis instance running on <code>localhost</code>.</p>
<pre><code class="javascript">host: &apos;localhost&apos;,
  port: 6379,
  ttl: &lt;redis session TTL in seconds&gt;,
  db: 0,
  pass: &lt;redis auth password&gt;
  prefix: &apos;sess:&apos;
</code></pre><!-- __LANG=%%__ -->
